  "prompt": "What's the size of a 4K image?",
  "response": "The size of a 4K image can vary significantly depending on several factors, including the image format, compression, and content. However, in terms of resolution, a 4K image typically refers to a resolution of 3840 x 2160 pixels.\n\nWhen considering file size:\n\n- **Uncompressed formats:** An uncompressed 4K image (such as a RAW file) can be quite large. For example, a 24-bit color depth (8 bits per channel) RGB image would be around 24.8 MB. This is calculated as follows:\n  - 3840 pixels * 2160 pixels * 3 bytes (24 bits) = 24,883,200 bytes, or approximately 24.8 MB.\n\n- **Compressed formats:** The file size can be significantly smaller if the image is saved in a compressed format like JPEG or PNG. A high-quality JPEG image might be around 5-20 MB, while a PNG file might be larger due to lossless compression, ranging from 10-30 MB or more.\n\nOther formats like HEIF or WebP might offer different levels of compression and file sizes.\n\nUltimately, the exact size of a 4K image file will depend on the specific details of the image and the format used for storage.",
